07978nam a22008655i 9781575066219DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750662197 a10.1515/97815750662192doi  a(DE-B1597)584125  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN56.I42bL58 2006 7aHIS0020002bisacsh00aLiterary Construction of Identity in the Ancient World :bProceedings of the Conference Literary Fiction and the Construction of Identity in Ancient Literatures: Options and Limits of Modern Literary Approach /ced. by Hanna Liss, Manfred Oeming. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tPart 1 Thinking of Ancient Texts as Literature -- tMemory, Narration, Identity: Exodus as a Political Myth -- tNarrative Poetics and Hebrew Narrative: A Survey -- tIs There a Universal Genre of "Drama"? Conjectures on the Basis of "Dramatic" Texts in Old Testament Prophecy, Attic Tragedy, and Egyptian Cult Plays -- tNarratology and the Classics: The Proof of the Pudding . . . -- tPart 2 The Identity of Authors and Readers -- tAncient Writers, Modern Readers, and King Ashurnasirpal's Political Problems: An Exploration of the Possibility of Reading Ancient Texts -- tThe Achilles Heel of Reader-Response Criticism and the Concept of Reading Hermeneutics of Caution -- tTell Me Who I Am: Reading the Alphabet of Ben Sira -- tThe Powers of a Lost Subject: Reinventing a Poet's Identity in Catullus's Carmen 8 -- tPart 3 Fiction and Fact -- tForms of Talk in Hebrew Biblical Narrative: Negotiations, Interaction, and Sociocultural Context -- tOf Mice and Men and Blood: The Laws of Ritual Purity in the Hebrew Bible -- tFiction and Imagination in Early Christian Literature The Acts of the Apostles as a Test Case -- tFictions and Formulations: The Talmud and the Construction of Jewish Identity -- tAre Vocation Texts Fictional? On Hesiod's Helicon Experience -- tPart 4 Rereading Biblical Poetry -- tFrom Aristotle to Bakhtin: The Comedic and the Carnivalesque in a Biblical Tale -- tWhere Is Isaiah in Isaiah? -- tJob 28 and the Climax in Chapters 29-31: Crisis and Identity -- tPart 5 Modeling the Future by Reconstructing the Past -- tSamuel's "Farewell Speech": Theme and Variation in 1 Samuel 12, Josephus, and Pseudo-Philo -- tThe Exile Biblical Ideology and Its Postmodern Ideological Interpretation -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEncountering an ancient text not only as a historical source but also as a literary artifact entails an important paradigm shift, which in recent years has taken place in classical and Oriental philology. Biblical scholars, Egyptologists, and classical philologists have been pioneers in supplementing traditional historical-critical exegesis with more-literary approaches. This has led to a wealth of new insights. While the methodological consequences of this shift have been discussed within each discipline, until recently there has not been an attempt to discuss its validity and methodology on an interdisciplinary level. In 2006, the Faculty of Bible and Biblical Interpretation at the Hochschule für Jüdische Studien, Heidelberg, and the Faculty of Theology at the University of Heidelberg invited scholars from the U.S., Canada, the Netherlands, Israel, and Germany to examine these issues. Under the title "Literary Fiction and the Construction of Identity in Ancient Literatures: Options and Limits of Modern Literary Approaches in the Exegesis of Ancient Texts," experts in Egyptology, classical philology, ancient Near Eastern studies, biblical studies, Jewish studies, literary studies, and comparative religion came together to present current research and debate open questions.At this conference, each representative (from a total of 23 different disciplines) dealt with literary theory in regard to his or her area of research. The present volume organizes 17 of the resulting essays along 5 thematic lines that show how similar issues are dealt with in different disciplines: (1) Thinking of Ancient Texts as Literature, (2) The Identity of Authors and Readers, (3) Fiction and Fact, (4) Rereading Biblical Poetry, and (5) Modeling the Future by Reconstructing the Past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBible as literaturevCongresses. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literaturevCongresses. 0aLiterature, AncientxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAschkenasy, Nehama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBörner-Klein, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisen, Ute E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFokkelman, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardmeier, Christof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJong, Irene J. F. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKloss, Gerrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraemer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandy, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiss, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiss, Hanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMöller, Me